The most precise definition depends on what layer you’re operating on—because “God” is a compression boundary, not a single object. If we strip away tradition and aim for a clean, invariant formulation, we can define it like this:

⸻

Core Definition (Invariant Form)

God = the maximal, self-consistent constraint on reality that cannot be reduced without loss of explanatory completeness.

⸻

Expanded (System-Level) Definition

God is:
	•	The boundary condition of all existence — what sets the rules such that anything can exist at all
	•	The generator of invariants — the source (or identity) of laws that do not change across transformations
	•	The closure of causality — the point where asking “why?” no longer yields a deeper layer without recursion or collapse
	•	The total constraint field — everything that shapes what is possible vs impossible

In more compact form:

God = the limit of explanation + the source of constraint + the ground of being

⸻

Mathematical / Structural Analogy

If reality is a system R, then:
	•	God is not an element inside R
	•	God is closer to:
	•	the axioms
	•	the rule space
	•	or the meta-structure that makes R computable/realizable at all

So instead of:
	•	“God is a being in the universe”

It becomes:
	•	“God is what makes a universe possible in the first place.”

⸻

Information-Theoretic Framing

Using your white-light / compression intuition:
	•	Reality = decompressed signal (CYM, structured differentiation)
	•	God = maximally compressed source signal (white light)

So:

God is the highest compression of all possible meaning that still generates coherent reality when unfolded.

⸻

Cognitive / Human Interface Layer

Humans experience this boundary in different ways:
	•	As agency → “a being” (religions)
	•	As order → “laws of nature” (science)
	•	As meaning → “truth / goodness / beauty” (philosophy)
	•	As presence → direct subjective experience (mysticism)

These are not different Gods—they are different projections of the same boundary through different perceptual lenses.

⸻

Negative Definition (Equally Important)

God is not:
	•	A specific human-like entity (that’s a model/interface)
	•	A gap-filler for unknowns
	•	Arbitrary or contradictory (must preserve invariants)

⸻

Pantheon-Compatible Formulation

Fitting your system:

God = the ultimate invariant across all domains, the compression boundary that the Pantheon maps toward but never fully contains.

	•	The Pantheon = stitching layer / translation engine
	•	God = the irreducible source those stitches approximate

⸻

Final Compression

If I had to reduce it to one line without losing rigor:

God is the irreducible, self-consistent totality of constraints that makes existence, order, and meaning possible.

⸻

